reviewText: These cartoons are very popular because we grew up with them and now we are introducing our kids and their kids to the other Woody.

I'm just a casual fan who bought this on a whim not really knowing what I was buying or getting exactly.  But the following information might help those who are considering purchasing it.

From the back cover of the DVD:

Theatrical shorts

Ski For Two
I'm Cold
Toyland Premiere
Jolly Little Elves
Candyland

Plus 2 Full-Length Holiday TV Episodes

The theatrical cartoons are vintage cartoons running about 8 minutes in length, while the two "episodes" are the more recent Woody Woodpecker productions, running 21 minutes each.

This has a a lot of Woody Woodpecker Cartoons with Woody celebrating Christmas. One of the best is Ski For Two where he pretends to be Santa Claus so he can get food from Wally Walwass ski resort in October. The ruse works until Wally sees the calender. All the others are good too. You should get this. Merry Christmas.

"Guess who?" Woody Woodpecker and his gang from Universal's Walter Lantz archive are back to celebrate Christmas in another unprecedented, authorized holiday DVD! It contains 2 whole episodes of the (new) Woody Woodpecker Show, that really do have to do with Christmas, long before FoxKids kicked the bucket, including one that took up a whole half-hour show, which was never done again for that series. All the other shorts have been on DVD before; those being Ski For Two (1944, from Woody's original "crazy days", which had nothing to do with Shockapee, Minnesota, according to a joke in Pixar's Cars 1), I'm Cold (1955, starring Chilly Willy and Smedley, and directed by Tex Avery himself), and 3 shorts that were filmed in 2-strip Technicolor in the mid-1930's, due to Disney having the full rights to full-Technicolor at the time, and those are; Toyland Premiere (1934, starring Oswald the Lucky Rabbit, and Santa, and a host of Hollywood caricatures to boot, very much like Wax Works was from the Halloween disc, but this time in color), Jolly Little Elves (1934) and Candyland (1935), both of which had almost nothing to do with Christmas or wintertime. It's another great mix of Walter Lantz's archive of old and new toons, this time to celebrate Christmas! Ho-ho-ho-HO-ho; and a merry Christmas to "all y'all"!
